<br>
What is the down-side for SOE on this one?  This lady goes public with her case in a misguided attempt to scare a settlement out of the company, and all across the country people see her rather unflattering visage saying stuff like &quot;The graphics are absolutely thrilling. They just haul you in.”  The news folks then cut to a scene in the game.<br>
<br>
You can BUY press like that, but it’ll cost you millions.<br>
<br>
So then SOE comes out and says something on the order of, “We are deeply saddened that this troubled young man took his life.  Our goal for EverQuest was to make a game as fun and deep as possible and provide many hours of quality entertainment to our customers; we sincerely hope that this incident will allow others to recognize this condition of existing mental illness in others.”<br>
<br>
A few rounds on Larry King Live, some interviews with “experts” who compare EQ to gambling and AD&amp;D, and countless screen-shots in local and nationwide newspapers.  EQ’s sales go up by 20% as teenagers across the country buy the game that was so much fun that a guy went without sleep for three days in order to play it.<br>
<br>
Finally, Sony opens the steel-reinforced door that holds their pack of lawyers at bay and lets them loose on this unfortunate woman and her assembled attorneys.<br>
<br>
Result one:  She loses and SOE is out absolutely nothing (as their lawyers are on retainer) while gaining millions of dollars in free advertising and a new level of brand recognition for their flagship game.<br>
<br>
Result two:  She wins and Sony has to pay a couple million dollars (reduced on appeal a couple years later) and is “forced” to place warning labels on their games.  They hold a big press conference to display the stickers on their new game, Star Wars Galaxies.<br>
<br>
And what do those stickers say, anyway?<br>
<br>
“Warning: game play may be addictive.”<br>
<br>
Bah.  Don’t throw me in that briar patch, please…<br>
